{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-02-17T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Ochagavía in Spain offers one of Navarre's most evocative winter scenes. This village of just over 480 residents, located in the Salazar Valley, 85 kilometres from Pamplona, stands out for its traditional architecture, with stone houses, steeply pitched roofs and a medieval bridge over the Anduña River that looks straight out of a postcard.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Navarra_ROW0874580487_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Navarra_ROW0874580487_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Ochagavía, Navarre, Spain","Copyright":"© PhotosTime/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260217_Navarra\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Ochagavia&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260217_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260217_Navarra"},"Ssd":"20260217","Name":"Navarra","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0874580487","FullDateString":"17. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Banff in Alberta, Canada, didn't grow quietly. It arrived with railways, hot springs and a vision: to protect places of rare beauty. In 1883, railway workers stumbled upon warm mineral water bubbling from Sulphur Mountain—an unlikely surprise in the cold sweep of the Rockies. The discovery drew attention quickly. By 1885, the surrounding land has been set aside as a protected reserve. What did that lead to? The beginnings of Banff National Park, Canada's first, and a blueprint the country would return to again and again.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BanffWinter_ROW0592236098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BanffWinter_ROW0592236098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Banff, Alberta, Canada","Copyright":"© Herbert Rong/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260216_BanffWinter\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Banff+town&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260216_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260216_BanffWinter"},"Ssd":"20260216","Name":"BanffWinter","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0592236098","FullDateString":"16. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Humpback whales are easily recognisable by their long pectoral fins and are known for their complex songs associated with breeding behaviour. Their predictable migrations bring them close to shore, turning them into both a cultural marker of the season and a focal point for early conservation efforts.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.MontereyHumpbacks_ROW0446556209_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.MontereyHumpbacks_ROW0446556209_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Humpback whales in Monterey Bay, California, USA","Copyright":"© Kiliii Fish/Cavan Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260215_MontereyHumpbacks\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Humpback+whales&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260215_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260215_MontereyHumpbacks"},"Ssd":"20260215","Name":"MontereyHumpbacks","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0446556209","FullDateString":"15. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At first glance, it looks like a love story that went a little too far. Pink hearts dangle from curved stems, each with a tiny white drop at the tip, as if the plant is mid-sigh. Meet the bleeding heart—proof that flowers can be dramatic without saying a word. Formally known as Dicentra spectabilis, it is a spring-flowering perennial native to eastern Asia. It can grow up to 60 centimetres tall and spread to nearly 75 centimetres wide, creating a graceful, almost poetic display.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ValentineHearts_ROW0216813332_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ValentineHearts_ROW0216813332_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Bleeding hearts","Copyright":"© Dorene Hookey/Cavan Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260214_ValentineHearts\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Bleeding+hearts&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260214_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260214_ValentineHearts"},"Ssd":"20260214","Name":"ValentineHearts","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0216813332","FullDateString":"14. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Before bridges, rivers set the pace of travel. Now, with bridges, people do. That shift explains why cross-border links like the Third Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge connecting Laos and Thailand matter. Bridges come in many forms, each built to meet a specific challenge. Arch bridges manage compression, suspension bridges span long distances and concrete box-girder bridges prioritise stability and load efficiency. This bridge uses the box-girder design, making it a practical choice for crossing the wide, fast-moving Mekong River.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.FriendshipBridge_ROW0019277166_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.FriendshipBridge_ROW0019277166_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Third Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge connecting Laos and Thailand","Copyright":"© chaiyut samsuk/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260213_FriendshipBridge\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Third+Thai+Lao+Friendship+Bridge&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260213_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260213_FriendshipBridge"},"Ssd":"20260213","Name":"FriendshipBridge","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0019277166","FullDateString":"13. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"When romance calls, this bird lifts one bright blue foot, then the other, like it's auditioning for a talent show with very strict colour rules. Not metaphorically. Literally. Meet the blue-footed booby. Widely associated with the Galápagos Islands, these seabirds range across the eastern tropical Pacific.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DarwinBooby_ROW9751594098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DarwinBooby_ROW9751594098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Blue-footed booby, Galápagos Islands, Ecuador","Copyright":"© Karine Aigner/TANDEM Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260212_DarwinBooby\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Blue+footed+booby&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260212_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260212_DarwinBooby"},"Ssd":"20260212","Name":"DarwinBooby","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9751594098","FullDateString":"12. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Death Valley National Park challenges first impressions. Spanning more than 1.34 million hectares across California and Nevada in the United States, it is the largest national park in the contiguous United States. Across this vast expanse, salt flats, volcanic hills, sweeping sand dunes and distant snowcapped peaks create a landscape shaped by time and extremes. From the soaring heights of Telescope Peak, which rises over 3,300 metres above the desert floor, to the depths of Badwater Basin, 86 metres below sea level, the park is a study in contrasts.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BadwaterFlats_ROW9539566313_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BadwaterFlats_ROW9539566313_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Salt flats in Badwater Basin, Death Valley National Park, California, USA","Copyright":"© Jim Patterson/TANDEM Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260211_BadwaterFlats\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Death+Valley+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260211_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260211_BadwaterFlats"},"Ssd":"20260211","Name":"BadwaterFlats","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9539566313","FullDateString":"11. feb. 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Floating lilies, glass-clear pools and a hidden world below: welcome to the Grand Cenote in Tulum, Mexico. This natural sinkhole formed thousands of years ago when collapsing rock let aquifer waters in. Over time, the chamber filled with clear freshwater that now connects a vast underground system of caves. At first, our eyes rest on the still surface. The water lilies we see in the image float without hurry, their broad leaves catching sunlight while supporting rich ecosystems underneath. These botanical wonders belong to one of the oldest flowering lineages on Earth, dating back more than 125 million years—older than most dinosaurs. Each bloom has evolved clever tricks to attract pollinators—beetles, bees, flies and even the wind—using scent, shape and timing to ensure survival in still water.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.TulumLilies_ROW3115035500_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.TulumLilies_ROW3115035500_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Water lilies at Grand Cenote, Tulum, Mexico","Copyright":"© Christian Vizl/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260224_TulumLilies\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Grand+Cenote+Tulum&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260224_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260224_TulumLilies"},"Ssd":"20260224","Name":"TulumLilies","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3115035500","FullDateString":"24. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The great egret is a striking large heron, easily recognisable by its pure white plumage, long neck and sharp yellow bill. Known for its cosmopolitan distribution, it occupies habitats around the world and adapts well to many aquatic environments. Adults measure about 94–104 centimetres in body length, with a wingspan of 1.3 to 1.5 metres and weigh about a kilogram, giving them a tall, elegant silhouette—roughly chest‑high when compared to a 2‑metre-tall person. As carnivores, they feed primarily on fish but also take amphibians, insects, small mammals and occasionally reptiles. Their patient hunting style, standing motionless before striking with sudden precision, is one of their most distinctive traits.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BavariaEgret_ROW2876151337_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BavariaEgret_ROW2876151337_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Great white egret, Upper Bavaria, Germany","Copyright":"© Konrad Wothe/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260223_BavariaEgret\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Great+white+egret&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260223_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260223_BavariaEgret"},"Ssd":"20260223","Name":"BavariaEgret","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2876151337","FullDateString":"23. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"'Shivering Mountain' is a dramatic nickname, but Mam Tor has earned it over hundreds of years. Rising above Castleton in England's Peak District, it lies within the United Kingdom's first national park, which spans more than 1,400 square kilometres. This landmark takes its name from Old English, 'mam' meaning 'mother,' a nod to the smaller hills it appears to cradle. Yet this 'mother mountain' is famously unstable. Its layers of shale and sandstone have caused landslips for centuries, including a collapse that permanently closed the A625 road in 1979.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.MamTorSunrise_ROW2203325574_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.MamTorSunrise_ROW2203325574_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"The hill of Mam Tor, Derbyshire, England","Copyright":"© john finney photography/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260222_MamTorSunrise\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Mam+Tor+hill&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260222_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260222_MamTorSunrise"},"Ssd":"20260222","Name":"MamTorSunrise","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2203325574","FullDateString":"22. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A red fox standing in the snowfall of Grand Teton National Park is more than a picturesque moment—it offers a glimpse into the resilience of one of North America's most adaptable predators. This small carnivore is instantly recognisable by its sharp gaze and thick, fiery coat that helps it thrive even in Wyoming's harsh winter conditions. Snow muffles sound, yet the animal's extraordinary hearing allows it to detect prey moving beneath the surface. You can almost imagine it pausing amid the drifting flakes, ears rotating, body perfectly still, waiting for the faintest rustle.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.TetonFox_ROW1833044776_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.TetonFox_ROW1833044776_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Red fox standing in snowfall, Grand Teton National Park, Wyoming, United States","Copyright":"© Radomir Jakubowski/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260221_TetonFox\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Red+fox&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260221_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260221_TetonFox"},"Ssd":"20260221","Name":"TetonFox","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1833044776","FullDateString":"21. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Yosemite National Park in California, United States, is renowned for its granite walls, dramatic waterfalls and striking light, all of which have inspired generations of artists. One of its most intriguing sights is the Firefall, a term that refers to two distinct events in the park's history. For decades, visitors gathered at Glacier Point to watch an artificial Firefall, in which embers were pushed off the cliff in a glowing stream of fire.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.AdamsFirefall_ROW1469118992_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.AdamsFirefall_ROW1469118992_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Horsetail Fall in Yosemite National Park, California, United States","Copyright":"© Jorge Villalba/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260220_AdamsFirefall\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Horsetail+Fall+Yosemite+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260220_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260220_AdamsFirefall"},"Ssd":"20260220","Name":"AdamsFirefall","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1469118992","FullDateString":"20. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Dragon's Eye sounds like something pulled from legend, and standing on Norway's Uttakleiv Beach in the Lofoten Islands, it's easy to see why. The formation, carved into ancient rock and framed by sand and sea, looks uncannily alive, as though the land itself is watching you. Shaped over thousands of years by ice and water, it has become one of the region's most captivating sights.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DragonsEyeRock_ROW1212085075_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DragonsEyeRock_ROW1212085075_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"The Dragon's Eye rock formation at Uttakleiv Beach, Norway","Copyright":"© reisegraf/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260219_DragonsEyeRock\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Uttakleiv+Beach+Norway&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260219_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260219_DragonsEyeRock"},"Ssd":"20260219","Name":"DragonsEyeRock","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1212085075","FullDateString":"19. feb. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"This species missed the domestication memo and kept going on its own terms. Say hello to Przewalski's horse, considered the last truly wild horse on Earth. Once widespread across Central Asia, it disappeared from the wild in the 1960s after decades of hunting, habitat loss and competition with livestock. Its survival depended on an unlikely lifeline: a small number of individuals captured by early 20th‑century collectors, which became the foundation of all modern Przewalski's horses.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PrzewalskisHorse_ROW1038206758_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PrzewalskisHorse_ROW1038206758_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Przewalski's horses","Copyright":"© Nemyrivskyi Viacheslav/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260218_PrzewalskisHorse\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Przewalskis+horse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260218_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260218_PrzewalskisHorse"},"Ssd":"20260218","Name":"PrzewalskisHorse","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1038206758","FullDateString":"18. feb. 2026"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"Dagens bilde","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD_LEARN_MORE":"Finn ut mer","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_DONATE_NOW":"Doner nå","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_FACT":"Hurtigfakta:","LOC_HOMEPAGE_GALLERY_CARD_TITLE":"Nylige hjemmesidebilder","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_GALLERY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"Hjemmesidebilde for {0}","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_TITLE":"På denne dag i historien","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"På denne dagen i {0} {1}","LOC_HOMEPAGE_SHARE_TOOLTIP":"Del dagens hjemmeside fra Bing","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERDOWNLOAD_TOOLTIP":"Last ned bildet. Dette bildet kan bare brukes som skrivebordsbakgrunn.","LOC_MUSCARD_DOWNLOAD_LINK":"Last ned dette bildet","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERNOTAVAILABLE":"Dette bildet kan ikke lastes ned som bakgrunnsbilde.","LOC_HOMEPAGE_INFO_TEXT":"Info","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK":"https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2127455","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK_TEXT":"Las